 model for a life of activism, a legacy of major contributions to international law, and-not least-an unpublished autobiography. Presented here for the first time is his own account of his life, from his boyhood on a small farm in Poland with his Jewish parents, to his perilous escape from Nazi Europe, through his arrival in the United States and rise to influence as an academic, thinker, and revered lawyer of international criminal law.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2020) 0aGenocidexPrevention. 0aHuman rights workerszPolandvBiography. 0aHuman rights workerszUnited StatesvBiography. 0aLawyerszPolandvBiography. 0aLawyerszUnited StatesvBiography. 0aWorld War, 1939-1945xAtrocities. 7aBIOGRAPHY & AUTOBIOGRAPHY / Political.2bisacsh1 aFrieze, Donna-Lee, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertYUP eBook-Package 2000-2015z978311066772108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertYale University Press eBook Package 2000-2013z978311053799440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780300188066423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780300188066.jpg  a978-3-11-053799-4  Yale University Press eBook Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  a978-3-11-066772-1  YUP eBook-Package 2000-2015c2000d2015  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles